title: HAM-STD HS1-404 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (41.87g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
NOTICE: Very thin airfoil. Print only if you're confident in your printer calibration skills.

I created the propeller with the HAM-STD HS1-404 airfoil. All tests were performed on the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (results below).

I printed this part with a slow setting, with the help of a 0.2mm nozzle at 0.04mm height per layer. I cleaned the final part using a Precision Knife

After this, I went on and sanded it using a 400 grit sandpaper.

Here are the thrust readings for a few voltage presets (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 11.91 grams
  • 2V => 22.46 grams
  • 2.5V => 33.47 grams
  • 3V => 41.87 grams

The files you can download consist of all shots taken during the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. If you'd like to have some fun with this propeller, you should get a 8520 coreless motor.

You should use the SLDPRT files, just in case you desire to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

Note: Airfoil plotted by using the matplotlib library in python.

title: Filament Spool Roller - Snap Fit 6x19x6mm Bearings 626zz

description.text:
A roller set I had was too wide for the bottom of my rubbermaid dry box containers. I liked rc101's snap fit design but it was for big bearings that I don't have handy. I've not had much luck with remix or edit of .stl files, so I drew up a bit different but similar snap together concept for smaller 626zz bearings (19mm OD 6mm ID and 6mm wide).

A single .stl file has a side and foot parts so print 4 to make a roller set. Each side has a single post for the bearing axis that lightly snaps into the opposing side pocket/hole. Then the feet press on with a tight fit to complete a solid filament roller base structure.

Update: SpoolRoller V3 file has the curved part of the side rail lowered 3mm to help reduce drag that a new spool might present. This is the file I recommend using.

My dry box parts started with this filament spool roller for a Rubbermaid 21Qt canister. I used PTFE Teflon tubing 3/16" ID x 1/4" OD for my 3mm filament and drilled out UKWEBB's https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2170536 Grommet for the feed nozzle. A rubber cap on the PTFE stub seals the container for storage.

I added a spacer cad file to keep the rollers appropriately spaced in the bottom of the dry box container. See another thing post for more details on the parts I used: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2401669

comments.text: I'm not a printing material expert and PLA characteristics haven't been something I've wanted to try yet. I did my first few of these in PETG and a few more in ABS and they're all nice and solid when tapped into the base/foot (so far so good here). Things that come to mind are shell thickness and infill. I typically do 4 all around and my print nozzle is .5mm so that's up to 2mm. Other thoughts might be using a little hotter temps to get better layer bonding?

description.text:
For years I used a cheap, plastic gadget I got in Istanbul. Squeezing lemons was easy, fun and clean. Eventually this tool broke and I decided to design one specifically for 3d-printing.

The lemon-bolt is easy to print, has no steep overhangs and is ready for use right from the printbed.

How to use it:

  • optional: role the lemon on a table to get even more juice out of it
  • press and screw the lemon-bolt into a lemon till it gets no further
  • massage/squeeze the lemon and the juice should flow
  • if you don't need all the juice - store the lemon with the bolt attached in the fridge.

check out the video: https://youtu.be/cFkVLB6J7Ig (apparently i got the most brittle lemon on earth...)

title: HAM-STD HS1-430 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (23.01g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
NOTICE: This is one FAT airfoil :). You might need to modify the SLDPRT file to extrude the hub a bit more if you're trying to print this.
I designed this micro drone propeller by using the HAM-STD HS1-430 airfoil. Testing was done using the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (results below).

Part printed at slow speed, by using a 0.2 nozzle at 0.04 layer height. The print was cleaned and deburred with an X-ACTO Knife

After this, it was sanded with a piece of 500 grit sandpaper.

These are the measurements for some voltage presets (you can also view these in the images taken during the test):

  • 1.5V => 4.12 grams
  • 2V => 9.71 grams
  • 2.5V => 13.19 grams
  • 3V => 23.01 grams

The files I included contain all pictures relevant to the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. If you want to tinker with the propeller, you should get a couple of 8520 coreless motors.

You can use the SLDPRT extension files, in case you wish to make your own changes to the propeller.

Notes: The airfoil plotted by using the matplotlib library in python.

description.text:
I have a Creality CR-10, and the built-in spool holder has a diameter that is larger than the discount spools I have found online. I have created and printed a previous spool holder, which you can also find here on Thingiverse.com but the tool compartment is not big enough to hold my tool for maintenance of the printer. It also is inaccessible when the spool is on, so I went back to the drawing board and came up with this Filament Spool Holder MK2.

I have adjusted the print files to be more accommodating to smaller print beds 200 mm by 200 mm is what I was shooting for. It comes with three pull-out drawers that are approx. 200 mm x 140 mm x 20 mm for the largest and 100 mm x 140 mm x 20 mm for the smallest. I kept the 20-mm diameter spindle but made the drawing file to more successful in actually printing by splitting half with a connecting rod in the middle. I also continued the successful construction pins and holes for easily assembly and tapered base to prevent from tipping. I have also included an extra file for a top cover with the idea that you may have your filament feeding 90deg from how you would like open your drawers.

description.text:
This design for a Honda Elite 250 trip reset button (1987-88 model years) was created from scratch. It is a replacement for Honda part number 37220-KM1-009. These buttons can be hard to find, so they are a good candidate for 3D printing.

Since the part is quite small, you will want to print at a resolution of 100um. Even then, it won't look as smooth as the original part.

We printed in ABS for a more weather resistant part; however, printing high resolution ABS can be tricky. We found the best results when we printed four parts at a time and put them near the four corners of the print bed. This gave the plastic time to cool before the next layer was printed. Without this, you may get too much heat on the small shaft and it may come out warped. If you have a hard time printing in ABS, just print some extras copies of the part in PLA and swap them out as needed.

If this part is of interest to you, then you will likely enjoy the Honda Elite CH250 Owners Group on Yahoo.

description.text:
This design for a Honda Elite 250 speedometer lens trim (1987-88 model years) was created from scratch. This piece is part of the speedometer lens (Honda part number 37211-KM1-831) and cannot be purchased separately.

Since the lettering on the part is quite small, you must print at a resolution of 50um. If you have a really good slicer, you may be able to get away with 100um.

The holes for the oil reset, trip reset, and clock adjust buttons are identical to the original part, so the rubber inserts from an old part can be used with this printed part. I spent some time in Fusion 360 creating the CAD file for the rubber inserts thinking that they could be printed in Ninja Flex, but never actually printed them. Contact me if interested and I would be happy to share the CAD file if I still have it.

The length of this part is just over 300 mm, so you will need to use a printer with a large print bed. We printed this part diagonally on the Prusa i3 MK2 print bed (250 mm x 210 mm) and it just barely fit.

We printed in ABS for a more weather resistant part; however, printing high resolution ABS can be tricky. If you have a hard time printing in ABS, just print some extras copies of the part in PLA and swap them out as needed.

If this part is of interest to you, then you will likely enjoy the Honda Elite CH250 Owners Group on Yahoo.

title: Prusa i3 MK2 fan shroud nozzle camera module

description.text:
I wanted to better see what was happening at the nozzle while printing. I found a small side on USB endoscopic camera module that I hoped would work and when it was delivered, seemed to be appropriate. It's only 640x480 but it's sufficient (as seen in the video)

A link to the camera module used: (I got mine from another seller but this one looks to be identical!)

https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Broaden-your-eyes-USB-90-degree-shooting-high-resolution-mini-endoscope-camera-module/925965018.html

I did have to desolder the cable that came with it and attach a USB cable but that's fairly simple. Windows noticed it was a webcam and got the relevant driver as soon as it was plugged in.

I had previously downloaded a model of the Prusa i3 MK2 and used this to arrange and create a modified fan nozzle that would hold the camera module with only a couple of clips, printed as part of the fan nozzle. You can get that model here:

https://grabcad.com/library/original-prusa-i3-mk2-printer-1

I did mangle the focus ring somewhat when trying to focus it in place. I'd suggest placing the shroud on the printer without the screw in, with the camera plugged in and remove it to alter the focus, replacing it each time until you get it to the right point.

Edit: Since making this, I was asked to print many thin items that filled the whole bed out of both ABS and PC. Turns out, making the shroud from PLA was a mistake. The fan never turns on for either of those so there is no air flow. Even worse, the heat damaged the camera module which made the image hazy and not useful.

I may look at this again some time, maybe adding a diverter to funnel some of the air blowing over the hot end heatsink toward the camera module but for now, I'll say it was a success for PLA but a failure for anything that needs a high bed temperature unless active cooling is provided for the camera.

title: GEEETech i3B/C/X: MK8 Refurbished Feeder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Hi,
at begin my GEEETech Pro i3B was come with “old fashion” metal feeder MK8, but last year I’ve update my i3B to i3C adding the second MK8, and I’ve get the new, black, plastic MK8, and a spare black feeder in order to have both extruder with the same feeder.
The new feeder have lot of nice, beautiful enhancements compared to old metal one, mains two are the easy filament insertion and the separation from barrel mounting block and MK8 itself, this last characteristic enable the unmounts of the MK8 from the printer without unmounts also the barrel and the extruder itself, in this way if you have a block in the barrel or in the nozzle you can easily unmounts the MK8, use the tool to push away the block and remount the MK8 without loose the alignment between the two nozzle, I love this option!
But the new feeder do not have the regulation for pre-load spring, and this can be a big issue with bad filaments!
To solve this issue I’ve redesign the feeder in order to integrate also in the new design this regulation, and it work!
I’ve start from original GEEETech design, copied with lot of patience and tricks, I have close both bottom and top in order to have something more strong, original injected parts are for sure stronger than any printed ones!
The pin where mount the bearing wheel cannot be strong enough if printed, so I’ve replaced with a screw, M3x10… I’ve also choose to use PTFE tube to ensure a quite filament movement.

Warning, part #5 have a log bridge, near 40mm, if your printer cannot afford this kind of bridge use support!

IF YOU “FALL IN LOVE” OF THIS DESIGN, PLEASE, REMEMBER THAT IT TAKE TIME TO BE CREATED, DESIGNED AND SHARED… SO “MAYBE” YOU CAN USE THE “TIP DESIGNED” BUTTON ON MY PROFILE!

description.text:
NOTE TO SIMPLIFY 3D USERS: several users reported that S3D doesn't slice this model correctly and I was able to reproduce it, the 0.2 part is fused at about Z=10mm http://i.imgur.com/99Qa9SV.png. If this happens to you, try one of these workaround (all worked for me) 1) rotate the part on the Z axis by 90 degrees, or 2) Click the menu entry Mesh | Separate Connected Surfaces before slicing.

This thing allows you to test the accuracy of your printing process and to determine the optimal clearance between moving parts (e.g. hinges). It was inspired by this Maker's Muse video https://youtu.be/TYuLVN3YHw8 and was designed with OpenScad (source file included here).

The test allow you to test up to 7 different clearances of your choice. Each clearance is tested using a cylinder and a rod that have the specified clearance between them. After printing, examine which of the clearances resulted in free moving parts, which can be freed by breaking them in using the screwdriver slot at the bottom and which are simply stuck.

Notes:

  • The model doesn't test tolerance of first layer which is typically more problematic due to 'squashing' it against the bed and always has ample clearance on the first layer.
  • The model has inside each cylinder an overhang of 45%. This is used to keep the rotating centers from falling out.
  • The clearances are measured horizontally, on the x,y plane, parallel to the printed layers. As a result, the actual clearance at the overhang sections is lower but I believe that the horizontal clearance of each layer is what matters.
  • With my 3D printing process (FFCP, PLA, S3D), I can release 0.2mm clearance but not 0.15mm clearance.

To customize this test click on the Customizer button in this page and change the model parameters.

My 3-year-old like to take sweets from the fridge. So i made this look. If it is glued it with Tesa power straps high enough on the fridge the kids can not open it anymore.

In addition to the 4 parts you need the spring from a pen and a short piece (same length as the uncompressed spring) from the ink tube (ideally you cut it on the back end - there should be no ink).

This design is made for a spring with an outer radius of about 4mm (as I found it in most pens).

The video shows it in real life:

https://youtu.be/BFEg5-z_P6o

Have fun :-)

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

To improve print stability the z-axis should not be in the direction where the highest forces act.
Please see the screen shot how the parts should be arranged.

Insert the spring in the slider (part 1) and insert the slider in the frame (part 3).

Pay attention the the hole in the slider is visible through the hole in frame.

Take some super glue and glue the knob (part 2) in the slider. This will also lock the slider in the frame.

Finally glue the parts (part 3 & part 4) on the fridge as it can be seen on the video. Pay attention that the aliginment matches.

Have fun.

This is a CAD drawing of a frame for a micro quadcopter. I designed it using Eachine QX95 frame as a template. It is basically a carbon copy of that frame or the closest I could get thus far :)

Started with AutoCAD Mobile, but finished with LibreCAD because AutoCAD mobile was too limiting.

I CNC milled the first test version out of vitroplast plate and it turned out great. You can see the result in the thing photos. The version you can download is a bit more improved over this first test version. I might be improving it more over time, so make sure to click "watch" to get the updates.

Happy and safe flying!

I've got my hands on a Pi0W and using the stable octopi 0.13 image. It doesn't setup the onboard wifi out of the box. (the distro was put togethor before Pi0W was launched). I used a usb hub, PiHut wifi dongle, keyboard and hdmi monitor and when booted it now finds the wifi dongle and connects. It's then possible to log in and update Raspbian:

sudo raspi-config
and enable ssh

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get dist-upgrade
sudo apt-get install rpi-update
sudo rpi-update

sudo shutdown now

Remove the Wifi dongle and restart the pi0w and the on-board wifi should be up and running.

There are some nice Raspberry Pi cases that will allow you to mount your RPi directly to a VESA mount on the back of a monitor or TV, but if you're like me, you have a RPi in an existing case, which you'd like to mount/dismount to the screen occasionally.

This design will allow you to do that. If you want to pop the RPi (in its case) off the monitor to work on for a while, you can, then pop it back on again, without having to play with screws.

The RPi will stand-away from the bracket and the monitor/TV a bit for air-circulation.

So the requirement is that your RPi case has screw-hanger holes at 40mm spacing. Both the RPI's in cases I have have the same spacing, so I'm guessing many other cases are the same.

You print this item, screw two small #6 round-head, or pan-head screws in the centre area, and mount the frame to the VESA holes in your monitor. Adjust the two centre screws until your case snugly grabs on, and you're all set.

Still a work in progress. A bit simplistic for now - expect a few tweaks as time allows. I can imagine a few cable tie-down spots, or clips at some point.

  • Connect to power to test
  • Solder/glue axle end back in place

title: Motorized Roller Shade Replacement Parts for 30 mm Tubes

description.text:
I bought motors to motorize my Bali Roller Shades. The kit with remote control is available on Amazon.com. They make it easy to remote control roller shades. The only problem was that the motor mount and drive sprocket were for a 38 mm roller tube. My Bali Shades have 30 mm tubes. This design provides the three parts needed to convert the shade motor for use with 30 mm tubes.

I printed the drive piece and end support in ABS. I printed the motor support adapter in TPA so that it would be soft like the original part. Using ABS would also work.

The original end support center post works with the new end support. It snaps right into the new part.

The 38 mm Roller Shade Motor:
http://www.amazon.com and then search for "B01DZQ43AI"

BOFU is the brand of this motor and remote kit.
